<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Where does the color of wine come from? Most people think that the color of the wine is the same as the color of the juice of the grape the wine came from. The juice in a green grape is clear and the juice in a dark red or black grape is also clear. Surprised? The color of the wine comes from the color pigment that is in the skin of the grape. White Zinfandel is a very sweet wine that is sort of lightly clear pink in color and is made from the Zinfandel grape. The Zinfandel grape is almost black in color. From the same grape, you can also get a dark red hearty non-sweet wine. How does this happen? In the white zinfaldel making process, the skin of the grape is seperated from the rest of the grape and then the juice is squeezed out. The result is that you eventually have a clear or pinkish wine because very little of the color pigment from the grape gets into the juice. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=554649">Fammaden Flycaster</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.hneguild.com" target="top">Heaven and Earth</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=fammadenflycaster>Fammaden Flycaster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:green;'>Tavern Patron</span></span><br>  Posts: 140<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(9/27/03 8:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3543.topic&index=82>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Picking walnuts out of my teeth?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.winespectator.com/Wine/Main/Feature_Basic_Template/0,1197,1852,00.html">This also says....</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Color in wine grapes is only skin deep. With the exception of hybrid varieties, all of the pigments, called anthocyanins, develop in the skin (not the pulp) during the ripening process. Anthocyanins are phenolic molecules commonly found in plants, and they account for the red, blue and purple colors in leaves, fruits and flowers. In grapes, their quantity and chemical structure varies according to a number of factors, such as grape variety, weather conditions and growing techniques. <br>
<br>
Just as people vary in skin tone, certain grapes naturally have more anthocyanin. Syrah, Cabernet Sauvignon and Petite Sirah are three of the darkest grape varieties, whereas Pinot Noir and Nebbiolo (the grape in Barolo and Barbaresco) are typically lighter. Since only the skin contains pigment, smaller berries with a higher ratio of skin to pulp yield deeper colors<br>
------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
It would seem that the type of grape does indeed alter the color of the wine, just not in the way you would expect. <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=554649">Fammaden Flycaster</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.hneguild.com" target="top">Heaven and Earth</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=vtynofsaryrn>Vtyn of Saryrn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:green;'>Tavern Patron</span></span><br>  Posts: 105<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(9/28/03 10:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3543.topic&index=83>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: well</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>my father has been brewing his own wine for about 15 years<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Wine is not brewed, it is vinted.  Sorry to be picky but I am a brewer by profession and this little mistake seems to bother me for some reason.<br>
<br>
The process of brewing involves several heating processes, including a full boil of no less than 1 1/2 hours.  The vinting process does not need to use a heating cycle at all and is  a much much more delicate process.<br>
<br>
Part of the reason why wine is so much more expensive than beer is the fact that when making wine it is much easier to infect your batch with a bacteria or other unwanted organisms that will spoil the wine or give it an off flavor.  The heating cycles used in brewing can all but eliminate such organisms from your batch so that the only real point of infection will occur in the fermentor (which is nice and cool).  <br>
<br>
Interestingly enough, many beer-makers throughout the world deliberately allow their batches to be infected by wild yeasts or other bacterias that produce.. odd flavors.  This happens most prevalently in Belgium today.  Also many old world European breweries refuse to use any kind of water treatment since the hard minerals and such in the ground water that they have used for centuries produce a specific off flavor that their brand is well known for.<br>
<br>
