I am still waiting for Garb to come back and tell me the reason some wines have a gunpowder or leather or smoke flavour is that they actually put gunpowder, leather or smoke into the wine. Though I admit he was pretty close on with the keep the corks wet post, there is no need to rotate the bottle. This is only done (AFAIK) in the champagne process:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Once this &quot;prise de mousse&quot; is done, a yeast deposit forms in the bottle. To eliminate it, bottles are placed on &quot;pupitres&quot;, a sort of easel with rows of holes to hold a bottle neck down. Turning and riddling will bring this sediment towards the neck: this is called &quot;remuage&quot;. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
